Coconut Choc Oatmeal Breakfast Cookie that can support lactation!

Here’s another version of my fave breakfast cookies that help my milk supply!

Oats are considered a galactagogue, meaning they may help with milk supply *along with increasing the demand at the breast.* I personally do notice a difference when I’m eating more oats!

2.5C rolled oats
1 cup chopped walnuts
1/2 tsp cinnamon
Pinch of salt
1 scoop of collagen (@needed collagen protein is what I use
3 eggs
1/4 cup melted butter
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
1/4 cup brown sugar
Dash of vanilla
1/2 C dark choco chips

Mix all of your ingredients together! If you can, let the
“dough” sit for 30 minutes so the oats can absorb some of the liguid otherwise it will run a little on the cookie sheet. Dollop onto a cookie sheet, making 6 large cookies, and bake at 350 for ~15 minutes or until golden brown!

Cucumber Mint Collagen Lemonade 🍋 

This just screams summer to me!

Cucumber is so hydrating + you get a boost of protein from the collagen which is so essential for postpartum recovery.

What you need:
1/2 a cucumber (or 1-2 minis)
1-2 mint leaves (fresh or dried)
1 packet of a lemonade mix
1 serving of flavorless collagen, I use my fave from @needed 
A squeeze of lemon juice if you like it more tart
8 oz water 
As much ice as you prefer (more if you prefer it like a slushy, you could also freeze your cucumber chunks)

Blend it all up and keep hydrating!

Let me know if you give it a try 🍋

SAVE FOR THE BEST SALMON RECIPE!

This was a summer fave of mine last year and it’s back!
Salmon is full of amazing baby building nutrients for a pregnant and postpartum mama! 

I love to airfry mine, but if you don’t have one then you can either bake or pan fry your cubes with a little olive oil. 

✨Take your salmon fillet and remove the skin, cut it into 1 inch cubes
✨In a bowl, add a drizzle of olive oil, sliced up basil, minced garlic to your preference, the juice of half a lemon, and as much lemon pepper as your heart desires with a dash of salt
✨Toss your cubed salmon in this mixture to marinate
✨You can bake, pan fry, or air fry this! I air fried mine at 350 for seven minutes in a preheated air fryer
✨I paired mine with coconut rice and a lemon Parmesan kale salad! Bon appétit!

Prairie Dust Shrimp!

This has been on repeat the last few months since having my baby because it comes together so quick and is full of flavor!!

What you need:
Shrimp (5-6oz per person)
1 lemon
2 Tbsp butter
2 Tbsp coconut oil
1 jar of cherry peppers
Rice + veggie for your side

Prairie Dust Seasoning:
(This makes more than you need to save for later)
1 Tbsp each of: onion powder, garlic powder, brown sugar, paprika, cumin
1-2 tsp chili powder
1/2 tsp salt
1 tsp pepper

Rinse and pat dry your shrimp, look for peeled and deveined, remove tails if needed. 

Chop your cherry peppers and slice your lemon in half.

Sprinkle shrimp with ~1 Tbsp prairie dust seasoning.

In a pan over medium heat, add coconut oil. Add your shrimp and cook 1 side until pink ~ 3 minutes, then flip.

In the middle of your pan, add butter until melted, add cherry peppers, and lemon juice + 1 tsp of prairie dust seasoning. Toss shrimp to coat in the sauce.

Pair with rice and veggies of choice! Enjoy!

Chocolate Zucchini Muffins with an Oat boost!

I have been on an oat kick since having my baby because I personally notice that is does support my milk supply! I try to add them to all my baked goods and this recipe is no different. Here’s what you need:

1 C ground oats (I put rolled oats in the blender until powdery)
1 C flour
��½ C unsweetened cocoa powder
��¼ C granulated sugar
��¼ C light brown sugar
��2 tsp baking powder
��1 tsp baking soda
��½ tsp salt
A dash of cinnamon
��1 large egg
��5 Tbsp unsalted butter melted
��1 tsp vanilla 
��1 C milk
��¾ C semisweet chocolate chips 
1.5 C shredded zucchini 

Mix your dry ingredients together and mix your wet ingredients together in a separate bowl. Shred your zucchini (a food processor works great for this) and set aside. 

Combine wet and dry ingredients until halfway mixed then add your zucchini. You don’t want to OVER mix your muffin batter, so fold everything to getting until JUST combined. 

Fill greased or lined muffin tins (12) and back at 375 for 20 minutes.

Breakfast prep for the week!

This time I used crescent roll dough as a crust to my casserole and it is now a fave around here! 

1 can of crescent rolls
18-24 eggs (depending on size!)
1 lb ground turkey sausage
Any chopped veg-clean out your fridge! 
1/2 cup shredded cheese
Salt and pepper

Place the dough in the bottom of your pan, layer your veg, eggs, cooked meat, cheese and S&P. 

Bake at 375 for 30 min, until the egg is set!

These breakfast bakes have been going strong for me since I was pregnant and I have no intention for stopping! 

I freeze them in individual portions and just heat in the microwave for ~2 min.

Before, during, and after pregnancy ✨ 

But why?

It’s good to be on a prenatal vitamin 3 to 6 months before trying to conceive to help build up Nutrient stores and support egg health. 

Of course, during pregnancy a prenatal can further support the increased nutrient needs and demands of growing a baby, and can also help fill gaps in the diet if you are feeling sick and can’t eat as much variety. 

Postpartum is a period of a lot of replenishment and recovery that needs to take place in your body and you should plan it to continue the prenatal vitamin for 3 to 6 months or longer if you continue breast-feeding beyond that point! 

If you want kiddos close together and plan to breastfeed, it may be a good idea to just stick with your prenatal until you are out of the baby making era 😘

Pumpkin spice German pancake for pregnancy and postpartum ✨
(or a Dutch baby or whatever you call it)! 

For the pancake:
3/4 stick of butter, melted in your cast iron skillet at 400 F. You want it HOT before you add the batter.
1/2 can of pumpkin purée
6 eggs
3/4 C ultrafiltered milk
1 C flour
Dash of pumpkin pie spice and extra cinnamon
1 tsp vanilla
1 tsp salt 

Blend all of it in a blender or food processor, add to your HOT skillet and bake for 15-20 minutes until puffy!

Pumpkin whip cream:
1/2 cup heavy cream
1/2 tsp pumpkin pie spice
1/2 tsp vanilla
Whip in a blender or with a hand whisk until it sets! (I don’t add sweetener but you can if you prefer) 

Glazed pecans/almonds:
1 Tbsp butter
2 Tbsp pure maple syrup
3/4 C pecans
1/4 C sliced almonds
1/2 tsp cinnamon 
Melt butter in a skillet with syrup until it starts to bubble, add your nuts and cinnamon and keep stirring for ~2-3 minutes until fully coated, remove from heat. 

Too your pancake with the cream and glazed nuts! Let me know if you try it this fall!

Mama and Me Meals: Steak Stroganoff at 7.5 months!

This did not go as I envisioned but that’s okay! 
I originally wanted to give her a large steak strip to gnaw/teeth with but it made more sense for us to pulse the stroganoff and serve it over the noodles for her to self feed, (especially with the weird mushroom texture). I also used frozen green beans and they were just the too short for my comfort level, I would have gave them to her if they were longer with less choking risk!

Another modification for BLW: I did not salt my meat or anything until after I had portioned hers out to decrease her sodium content. She did get pepper on it as it was cooking!

She did okay with this meal but it definitely was not her favorite. 

Recipe:
1 lb steak chunks (ours was actually elk)
1 onion
2-3 garlic cloves
16 oz mushrooms, washed and sliced 
1 can of cream of mushroom soup
1/2 can of water
4 oz cream cheese
12 oz egg noodles

Cook your meat over medium heat, add the garlic, onion, and mushrooms when the meat is about 1/2 done. Cook for about 2-3 minutes then add the soup, water, and cream cheese. Simmer over medium-low heat until meat is cooked (all the way for baby). 
Prep your noodles per package instructions.

Portion baby first to let it cool: pulse about 1/4 cup of the meat/sauce mixture with 1-2 ice cubes to cool and thin it out, until no large chunks remain. Serve over noodles. 

Salt and pepper yours to your liking and serve with veggie of choice. 

I will say, pulsing your meal in a blender is great if it’s hard to adapt to “baby friendly”. We have done this before when I made a chunky stew and served it with her spoon to self feed!

I personally really loved my pregnancy but I know so many moms do not…and that is OKAY! 💕

We are all good mamas!

SAVE this Peach Oatmeal Bake!

The best recipes come when I’m just throwing stuff together in the kitchen! This is a must during peach season!

1 ripe banana
2 cups oats
3 eggs
1 tsp vanilla
Dash of salt
Dash of cinnamon
1 cup of pecans
1-2 peaches

Mash your banana and mix with the eggs and vanilla. Add your oats, nuts, salt and cinnamon until combined.
Chop your peaches and fold into your mixture, leave some to top your oats.

Pour into a greased round cake pan or 8x8 baking dish and top with your remaining peaches.

Bake at 375 for 18-20 min!

“But, I’m burning so many calories to make milk”

While that is true, most women are often a lot more hungry and eating a bit more! 

AND  the hormone prolactin which is released whenever you lactate has shown to be linked to slower weight loss in some women’s bodies. 

A nutrient dense diet with real, whole foods and regular physical activity can support a healthy weight loss while still maintaining milk supply, but realistic expectations are also needed because the weight won’t just “fall off” with the extra energy expenditure in most  lactating women!

I’m Lauran, a pre/postnatal dietitian and I can help you lose the weight in a healthy and maintainable way! DM me “WEIGHT” and we can chat 💕

What I am eating at 8 months postpartum!

I am nursing (pumping at work), losing the baby weight, and focusing on nutrient dense foods that are satisfying and tasty!

Reminder: we all have different Nutrient needs, and what I’m eating doesn’t have to be what you are eating. Also, this is not everything I eat in a day, just what I took to work!

VEG FILLED PASTA SALAD LUNCH PREP

Lunch is often a last minute thought for me, so taking some time to prep something nutrient dense makes a world of a difference for me as a busy mama.

Pasta salad:
1 C each of chopped cabbage, bell pepper, carrots, cucumbers
1/4 cup chopped red onion
1 package of @enjoybrami lupini beans
1 C dry pasta, cooked per package directions and cooked 

Dressing:
1/4 C olive oil
1/4 C Greek yogurt
1-2 tsp sriracha 
1 garlic clove, minced
Zest + juice of 1 lemon
3 Tbsp feta
Salt and pepper

I added chicken on top of mine but there is a decent amount of protein from the beans. This made ~ 3 lunches for me!

Postpartum Nutrition Tips from a Registered Dietitian

Continue your prenatal vitamin: there is a lot of replenishment that your body needs to do, whether you are nursing or not. Plan to continue it for at least 3 to 6 months or until you finish lactating.

Protein and Collagen: good quality protein and collagen Sources are so helpful for muscle tissue rebuilding in the recovery process of postpartum. Your body went through a lot regardless of how you gave birth, and major recovery needs to happen.

Don’t skip meals: I know it can be really hard when you’re so focused on taking care of your child and we often neglect to feed ourselves, especially early on. Your body needs to eat so that you have adequate energy to take care of your baby and heal yourself (plus support healthy weight loss if that’s your goal). 

Aim for 100 ounces of fluid: hydration is so important, and whether you are nursing or not. It helps you stay energized and can support milk supply if you are are lactating. Adding some electrolytes and minerals is often a good idea to further support hydration.

BONE BROTH RECIPE

I am a huge fan of bone broth in both pregnancy and postpartum. It’s an excellent source of glycine, a precursor to collagen, which is essential to our tissue growth and repair, stretching (or shrinking) skin, and is excellent for our gut health! 

In the last I’ve made it in a crock pot or stove top and it take literally all day, but if you have a pressure cooker or instapot, then it can be done in 3 hours!

You need:
1-3 rotisserie chicken carcasses (or turkey, or beef bones etc)
3 Tbsp acid - vinegar, lemon juice or both
Aromatics of choice - onion, garlic, green onion, celery, carrots, ginger, sage, etc
Salt and pepper
Add water until you hit the Max fill line

Cook on high pressure for 2 hours, then natural release for 30-60 min. 
Strain all of the bones and additives out of your broth and enjoy!

Let it cool before you store it, up to 2-3 months in the freezer or 3 days in the fridge.

Honestly, before I got pregnant, I had no idea how I would respond and react to the changes that my body would go through. I’ve always had a pretty good relationship with my body, but I was definitely fearful of the weight gain and the eventual weight loss (or lack of) in postpartum. 

I can definitely say that loving your body in every stage is  HARD. And some days I definitely haven’t.

The further postpartum I am, my perspective has started to change. I am amazed that my body grew this little human, and I have nourished her completely by myself with the milk that my body has created for her. That’s pretty amazing!

The progress back to “my old self” has been slow but it’s honestly worth it to see the little munchkin grow. 

These past couple of months is when I have started to actually see real changes in my body as I have created a late postpartum nourishment and health focused program while maintaining my milk supply and losing a little weight. 

The program drops in January, just in time for the new year. But… If you have read this far, you can get the black Friday deal that I am offering through the end of November! SAVE THIS! White chicken chili for me and my 8 month old!

Soups can be a little tricky, this is pretty much what we do whenever we have soup and give her some.

Recipe:
1 onion diced
2-4 garlic cloves minced
2 cans of green chilis
2 cans of northern beans (or any)
1-2 Tbsp cumin
1/2 cup of heavy cream 

4 oz cream cheese 
1-2 cups of corn
1 can of jalapeños (optional)
16 oz shredded cooked chicken
16-20 oz bone broth
Salt and pepper to taste

In a pressure cooker, sauté onions and garlic until aromatic, add your green chilies and your beans, then your broth, and bring to a boil, add the chicken, cream, and cream cheese (this is where you can pull out baby’s portion and shred their chicken and mash the beans). Then add corn, jalapeños, salt, and pepper to taste. 
I topped mine with  shredded cheese and cilantro.

How do you serve soup to baby?

SAVE this recipe!

This would be a great holiday meal side dish to take to your party!

Roast acorn squash with cranberries in olive oil for 20 to 25 minutes. You can start the squash for 15 minutes and then add your cranberries, once done sprinkle of cinnamon.

For the dressing: add 3 tablespoons balsamic vinegar, quarter cup of olive oil, 3 tablespoons of maple syrup, 2 tablespoons of Dijon mustard, sprinkle of salt and pepper to taste all whisk together. Pour that on your chopped kale and massage into it for tenderness and to remove the bitterness from the kale.

Top with sliced apples, feta, cinnamon pecans, and your roasted squash and cranberries. Enjoy!

✨Fruit and veggies should taste good even if it means you have to add a little fat or sweetness to the meal✨

A big thing that I focus on with my postpartum clients is getting in a variety of fruits and vegetables throughout the day, and this is a fun recipe to include!

This cranberry salsa hits the spot!

1 package fresh cranberries
1/4 cup sugar (to balance out any bitterness in the berries)
1 small jalapeno
1 red onion
1 bunch of cilantro
A couple green onion sprigs
Juice from 2 limes
A couple pinches of salt

This is amazing by the spoonful, with tortilla chips (I didn’t have any so I air fried a couple of corn tortillas and it was perfect), crackers, on tacos, fish, whatever!

Let me know if you are making this!

This is surprisingly easy and so nutrient dense!

For the fish:
3-4 filets of white fish (barramundi, tilapia, halibut, etc)
1/3 C panko
2/3 C unsweetened coconut shreds
Egg wash
1/2 C flour to dredge

mix the coconut and Panko together in one bowl, egg, whisk and another bowl and flour and another. Pat dry your fish fillets and dredge in flour and egg then the coconut breadcrumbs.

Fry in a nonstick pan with a little bit of butter or olive oil 4 to 5 minutes each side.

Coconut rice:
1 can of coconut milk 
1/2 can of water
1.5 C rice

Boil your coconut milk and water, add the rice and bring back to a boil then cover and simmer until liquid is absorbed and rice is fluffy.

for the pineapple salsa: chop half of a pineapple, one jalapeño, half of a red onion, half of a bell pepper, cilantro, to taste, and juice from one lime, and a dash of salt.

Easiest bone broth ever!

Turkey, rotisserie chicken, whatever carcass you want to use! Add water, splash of vinegar, then any veggies you have and add to your pressure cooker on High for 2 hours. 

Strain and sit out to cool a bit before transferring to jars to store in the fridge or freezer. 

Mine was very gelatinous this go around as it cooled, which means more collagen 🙌🏼

Minerals are often referred to as our body’s “spark plugs.”

Your car could be full of gasoline, but without your spark plugs, you’re not going very far! 

In our own body, minerals are essential to every single cells function. We need them to make hormones, energy, enzymes, and they support pretty much every body process!

As a dietitian, I had spent a full year working with other moms who were pregnant or trying to conceive before I was even at that stage myself, so I definitely had some background going into it.

Things I prioritized:
✨protein at each meal and snack
✨100 oz fluid daily
✨lots of fruits and veggies for fiber + micros
✨prenatal vitamins at least 3-6 months before 
✨movement I enjoyed, both low and high intensity
✨carb balance and pairing
✨reducing stress + saying “no” when needed

These are important fertility supporting practices to focus on, and they are things to take with you into pregnancy so everything is not a huge lifestyle change when that time comes!
